<treatment><number>45a</number><TaxonIdentification Status="ACCEPTED"><genus_name>Helianthus</genus_name><species_name>nuttallii</species_name><species_authority>Torrey &amp; A. Gray</species_authority><subspecies_name>nuttallii</subspecies_name></TaxonIdentification><TaxonIdentification Status="SYNONYM"><genus_name>Helianthus</genus_name><species_name>nuttallii</species_name><subspecies_name>canadensis</subspecies_name><subspecies_authority>R. W. Long</subspecies_authority></TaxonIdentification><description>Plants usually 200–300 cm. Leaves mostly alternate; blades narrowly to broadly lanceolate, apices acute to acuminate, abaxial faces hispid to hispidulous. Phyllaries: abaxial faces ± glabrate or sparsely hairy (longer hairs 0.5–1 mm).</description><phenology>summer</phenology><phenology>jun</phenology><phenology>jul</phenology><phenology>aug</phenology><phenology>fall</phenology><phenology>sep</phenology><phenology>oct</phenology><phenology>nov</phenology><habitat>moist open places</habitat><habitat>ditches</habitat><habitat>roadsides</habitat><elevation>(300–)1200–2700 m;</elevation><ca_distribution>Alta.</ca_distribution><ca_distribution>B.C.</ca_distribution><ca_distribution>Man.</ca_distribution><ca_distribution>Sask.</ca_distribution><us_distribution>Ariz.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Calif.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Colo.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Idaho</us_distribution><us_distribution>Kans.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Mo.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Mont.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Nebr.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Nev.</us_distribution><us_distribution>N.Mex.</us_distribution><us_distribution>N.Dak.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Okla.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Oreg.</us_distribution><us_distribution>S.Dak.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Utah</us_distribution><us_distribution>Wash.</us_distribution><us_distribution>Wyo.</us_distribution><discussion>Plants in the Dakotas and south-central and ea